quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to make the animation complete in 5 seconds:
[!raw!]
-webkit-{0}: {1}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The animation-name Property[/h1]

[b]animation-name[/b] property defines which animation to use. 
In this example, the name of the animation is set to [b]colorchange, [/b]which matches the defined keyframes.

[b]The CSS:[/b][code format="css" codeId="631"]div {
   animation-name: [b]colorchange;[/b]  
   animation-duration: 5s;
}
@keyframes [b]colorchange[/b] {
   from { width: 0px; }
   to { width: 100px; }
}[/code]
The [b]animation-duration[/b] property specifies the duration of the selected animation in seconds.
[note]If the animation name does not match any keyframe rule, the animation [b]will not execute[/b].[/note]

quizzes.question:
Add an animation named sizechange, which starts after 2 seconds, runs for 5 seconds, uses the ease function, and loops forever.
[!raw!]
.test {
animation-{0}: sizechange;
animation-{1}: 5s;
animation-timing-function: ease;
animation-{2}: 2s;
animation-iteration-count: {3};
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]animation Property[/h1]

Consider the following example: [code format="css" codeId="635"]div {
   animation-[b]name[/b]: colorchange;
   animation-[b]duration[/b]: 3s;
   animation-[b]timing-function[/b]: ease-in;
   animation-[b]delay[/b]: 1s;
   animation-[b]iteration-count[/b]: infinite;
   animation-[b]direction[/b]: reverse;
}[/code]
A single [b]animation [/b]property can be used to achieve the same result as the above code:[code format="css" codeId="636"]div { 
   animation: colorchange 3s ease-in 1s infinite reverse;
}[/code]
[note]The order in which each property is declared in the shorthand declaration is important and cannot be altered, or the animation will not work properly.[/note]
